WEBVTT

1
00:00:09.980 --> 00:00:13.620
Have you been to an interview recently, been perfectly qualified

2
00:00:13.660 --> 00:00:16.890
for the role, you've answered all the questions correctly, but

3
00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:21.060
still been rejected? Well, the answer could lie in your

4
00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:25.220
body language. Recent studies suggest that only seven percent of

5
00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:29.360
your communication are the actual words you say. Thirty-eight percent

6
00:00:29.740 --> 00:00:34.160
are certain vocal elements like your intonation, but fifty-five percent

7
00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:38.100
is your non-verbal, things like your facial expression, your gestures,

8
00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:40.320
your posture. So this video is going to look at

9
00:00:40.340 --> 00:00:42.680
the messages you've been sending out with your body language

10
00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:44.860
and how to tweak those to make sure you're sending

11
00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:49.660
out all the right signals at your next interview. So

12
00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:52.440
think about your body posture. A very natural thing for

13
00:00:52.460 --> 00:00:55.940
people to do is to slouch, uh, in the chair

14
00:00:56.020 --> 00:00:59.580
or fold their arms, and this looks like you're making

15
00:00:59.620 --> 00:01:03.140
yourself smaller, wrapping yourself up, and the signal you're giving

16
00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:05.440
off to the interviewer is that you're defensive or nervous.

17
00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:09.050
Instead, open up your body. Don't cross your legs or

18
00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:11.960
fold your arms, um, but engage slightly forward from the

19
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.720
waist, and this will give the appearance to the interviewer

20
00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:19.730
that you're interested. If you're, um, jiggling about a lot

21
00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:22.700
in the chair, um, keeping changing your body posture, or

22
00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:24.640
you're playing with a button on your shirt or the

23
00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:28.050
ring or other objects, um, you're going to appear anxious

24
00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:29.940
and nervous, and certainly the interviewer is going to be

25
00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:32.300
less inclined to have confidence in you. So a really

26
00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:36.120
good tip is to first slow your breathing down. This

27
00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:38.440
will slow your heart rate and make you feel less

28
00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:43.340
nervy. Keep your hand gestures steady and only to emphasize

29
00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:46.910
a point. Palm upwards signifies that what you're saying is

30
00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:50.420
honest and trustworthy. Um, touching your heart signifies that what

31
00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:53.750
you're saying is genuine. Steepling is a sign of confidence.

32
00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:57.710
Conversely, clasping your hands is a sign of self-comfort and

33
00:01:57.740 --> 00:02:02.600
anxiety, so make sure you avoid these. Mirroring the

34
00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:05.940
interviewer is a, an effective technique, but it needs to

35
00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:10.440
be done very subtly. Mirroring hand movements or positive gestures,

36
00:02:11.300 --> 00:02:14.450
waiting ten seconds, though, before you do it yourself. Um,

37
00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:17.940
you can also mirror your speech, so, um, their vocabulary,

38
00:02:18.120 --> 00:02:21.920
their jargon, um, the rate or volume, um, of their

39
00:02:21.940 --> 00:02:25.800
speech. People trust those that are similar to themselves, so

40
00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:29.220
this makes the interviewer, um, feel at ease, and you're

41
00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:33.840
more likely to build rapport with them. This is so

42
00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:37.940
important. Interviewees often avoid the gaze of the interviewer or

43
00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:41.300
they look down. Um, but by looking at the interviewer's

44
00:02:41.360 --> 00:02:46.160
eyes, you're asserting your confidence, your trustworthiness. Instead of staring

45
00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:48.360
at the interviewer, alternate your gaze between the left eye,

46
00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:50.540
the right eye, the mouth, maybe every three seconds, just

47
00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:54.280
enough to see the color of the interviewer's eyes. For

48
00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:57.920
panel interviews, make sure you look at everybody, but specifically

49
00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:00.020
focus your attention on the person who's asking you the

50
00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:04.600
question or is speaking at the time. To avoid line

51
00:03:04.700 --> 00:03:08.120
signals, um, the main rule is avoid touching your face,

52
00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:11.680
so especially your nose, your mouth, your ears, your sideburns.

53
00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:14.660
These are all signs that will suggest to your interviewer

54
00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:16.400
that you're being dishonest with the way that you're answering

55
00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:21.010
their questions. So the, the handshake is an obvious one,

56
00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:23.860
um, but so many people get this wrong. It's the

57
00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:28.880
unspoken word that initiates conversation in any social or professional

58
00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:33.640
get-together. Too firm, and you'll seem too dominant. Too weak,

59
00:03:33.660 --> 00:03:37.800
and you'll seem under-confident. Instead, always initiate the handshake, match

60
00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:42.530
the interviewer's grip, apply the one-two second rule, smile, and

61
00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:45.510
repeat their name. By putting these body language tips into

62
00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:48.240
practice, you'll be giving off the right impression at your

63
00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:51.549
next interview. Now all you need to worry about is

64
00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:52.460
what you're actually going to say.
